e a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Henri","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Henry</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":48,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":59,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henri Hiscoxe  Hiscockes was born in 1510, in All Cannings, Wiltshire, England, his father, Richard Hiscockes, was 20 and his mother, Margeret Husdale, was 20. He married Isabel Elizabeth Marr in 1530, in All Cannings, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1569, in All Cannings, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1510–1569":"1510–1569","1515–1569":"1515–1569","1501–1560":"1501–1560","1530–1569":"1530–1569","1532–1587":"1532–1587","1542–1586":"1542–1586","1556–1586":"1556–1586","1490–1570":"1490–1570","22 May 1542":"22. mai 1542","1560":"1560","1570":"1570","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1556":"1556","1501":"1501","1510":"1510","1532":"1532","17 July 1560":"17. juuli 1560","1587":"1587","1586":"1586","1542":"1542","1530":"1530","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","All Cannings, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"All Cannings, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","All Cannings, Wiltshire, England":"All Cannings, Wiltshire, England","Lacock, Wiltshire, England":"Lacock, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1510–1569":"1510–1569","1515–1569":"1515–1569","1501–1560":"1501–1560","1530–1569":"1530–1569","1532–1587":"1532–1587","1542–1586":"1542–1586","1556–1586":"1556–1586","1490–1570":"1490–1570","22 May 1542":"22. toukokuuta 1542","1560":"1560","1570":"1570","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1556":"1556","1501":"1501","1510":"1510","1532":"1532","17 July 1560":"17. heinäkuuta 1560","1587":"1587